Python Lists Cheat Sheet - Complete Notes
This document extracts all list-related information from the Python Summary Cheat Sheet - 2 page, including Working with Lists topics and List Methods. It also adds one simple example for each list method for easier practice. [page:9]
List Basics
A list is described as the most versatile Python data structure and it holds an ordered sequence of items. Elements of a list are accessed using indexing. [page:9]
list_a = [5, "Six", 2, 8.2]
print(list_a[1])
# Output: Six
Iterating Over a List
A for loop can be used to iterate over each item in a list. The cheat sheet shows printing each item one by one. [page:9]
list_a = [5, "Six", 8.2]
for item in list_a:
    print(item)
# Output:
# 5
# Six
# 8.2
List Concatenation
The + operator concatenates lists, similar to string concatenation. [page:9]
list_a = [1, 2]
list_b = ["a", "b"]
list_c = list_a + list_b
print(list_c)
# Output: [1, 2, "a", "b"]
List Slicing
Obtaining a part of a list is called list slicing. Extended slicing can use a step value to extract alternate items. [page:9]
list_a = [5, "Six", 2]
list_b = list_a[:2]
print(list_b)
# Output: [5, "Six"]
list_a = ["R", "B", "G", "O", "W"]
list_b = list_a[0:5:3]
print(list_b)
# Output: ["R", "O"]
Reversing and Negative Slicing
Using -1 as the step reverses the order of items in a list. The cheat sheet also shows slicing with negative indices and negative step size. [page:9]
list_a = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
print(list_a[::-1])
# Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
list_a = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
print(list_a[-3:-1])
# Output: [3, 2]
list_a = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
print(list_a[4:2:-1])
# Output: [1, 2]
Membership Operators
The in operator checks whether a value is present in a sequence, and not in checks whether a value is absent. [page:9]
numbers = [1, 2, 3]
print(2 in numbers)
print(5 not in numbers)
# Output:
# True
# True
Nested Lists
A list can be an item inside another list. The cheat sheet also shows how to access the nested list and an item inside that nested list. [page:9]
list_a = [5, "Six", [8, 6], 8.2]
print(list_a[2])
# Output: [8, 6]
list_a = [5, "Six", [8, 6], 8.2]
print(list_a[2][0])
# Output: 8
List Methods
The cheat sheet lists ten list methods: append, extend, insert, pop, remove, clear, index, count, sort, and copy. Their uses are shown below with one extra practice example for each method. [page:9]
append()
append() adds an element to the end of the list. [page:9]
fruits = ["apple", "banana"]
fruits.append("mango")
print(fruits)
# Output: ["apple", "banana", "mango"]
extend()
extend() adds all the elements of a sequence to the end of the list. [page:9]
a = [1, 2]
b = [3, 4]
a.extend(b)
print(a)
# Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]
insert()
insert() inserts an element at a specified index. [page:9]
colors = ["red", "blue"]
colors.insert(1, "green")
print(colors)
# Output: ["red", "green", "blue"]
pop()
pop() removes the last element from the list. [page:9]
nums = [10, 20, 30]
nums.pop()
print(nums)
# Output: [10, 20]
remove()
remove() deletes the first matching element from the list. [page:9]
nums = [1, 2, 3, 2]
nums.remove(2)
print(nums)
# Output: [1, 3, 2]
clear()
clear() removes all items from the list. [page:9]
items = ["pen", "book"]
items.clear()
print(items)
# Output: []
index()
index() returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified value. [page:9]
letters = ["a", "b", "c", "b"]
print(letters.index("b"))
# Output: 1
count()
count() returns the number of elements with the specified value. [page:9]
nums = [1, 2, 2, 3, 2]
print(nums.count(2))
# Output: 3
sort()
sort() sorts the list. [page:9]
nums = [4, 1, 3, 2]
nums.sort()
print(nums)
# Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]
copy()
copy() returns a new list and does not modify the original list. [page:9]
a = [1, 2, 3]
b = a.copy()
print(b)
# Output: [1, 2, 3]
